Rating: 3
This is a great base recipe for a tagine but requires some tinkering. I doubled all the spices and sub'd low sodium chicken broth for water as the others suggested. But there are a few other things you can do to make the dish exceptional and full of flavor. 1) Use skinless dark chicken ON the bone. The bone has a tremendous amount of flavor that transfers to the tagine. Also the dark meat holds the spice better; 2) Dry rub the chicken with cinnamon, ginger, cumin, tumeric, salt and pepper and let it sit for 30min+; 3) Brown chicken before it goes in pot; 4) Add quartered turkish apricots when you add the carrots (they have some sugar that balances the spices); 5) Add a tsp of lemon zest; 6) Add 1-2 tbsp of sugar at very end - eliminates any bitterness and helps balance the dish and all the various components. I served the tagine over an authentic couscous with hot peppers in it. Delish!

