I lived in northern Morocco for several months and this is the most authentic tasting recipe (and final product) I've tasted State-side. I don't ever remember seeing greenbeans in anything I ate(could be a regional ingredient), so I substituted with fresh frozen peas towards the end. If you slice the lemons VERY thin, the slices literally dissolve into the tagine and is not bitter. Be very sure to remove all seeds and the hard, thick ends, and the white stringy middles. This dish requires all the spices (it's basically the ras el-hanout blend which, in other recipes on Epicurious is supposedly only found in specialty stores) and the herbs (the mint at the end combinded with the coriander, cumin, paprika, lemon and cilantro seals the dish). This is fantastic. I also just halved chicken breasts to put in the pot because I hate eating chicken off the bone. One twist would be to add some golden raisin at the end (not too early or they will get too hot to eat). This is not common, and usually raisins and currants are eaten with couscous dishes, but, it lends to the Moroccan flavour.

