Rating: 4
What an excellent dish with so many possibilities. I really only used the recipe as a basis to do what I wanted and get it to taste the way I like. Good writeups from others helped form the perfect dish. I definitely stepped up the spices, used chicken broth instead of water and didn't add the lemon slices. Instead I did the Caribbean technique of letting the chicken sit after its been washed and skinned in some fresh squeezed lime juice, salt and pepper....about 30 minutes while I prepared the other ingredients. Another important thing is the right cookware, Le Creuset if just my favorite and allows for such great browning and even cooking. I did brown the chicken first. Remove to platter. Then saute the onions, garlic and ginger. Add the spices (be generous). Then return the chicken. Then add diced tomatoes (I used the canned ones, ok scold me later), chicken broth and some saffron tea I picked up from another recipe...you basically just steep regular tea as you would but throw in some threads of saffron. Added parsley and cilantro, didn't have mint and didn't feel like buying it...didn't have anything else to make with it. Added the carrots, grean beans and garbanzos...I like the other writeups recommendations for either butternut or acorn squash or even zucchini, either would be great but felt the carrots just did go better with green beans and garbanzos. I also added dried figs which made a lovely balance with the spiciness. And also kamalata black olives, I know green in tagine but I like black...go with what you like! I did slow cook it for about 2 hours (barely noticeable boil level). The result was the most integrated tasty full bodied sauce, albeit it thin unless you add thickener...which you could pull some of the broth mix in some tomato paste and thicken it that way. Best served over couscous. Great dish to be creative with! Enjoy!

